iments | Common Negative Sentiments |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| [Pacific Life](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/life-insurance/pacific-life-insurance-review/) | 5.3 | Somewhat likely to recommend | Competitive rates and decent customer service | Inadequate communication and difficulty in the claims process |\n| [Northwestern Mutual](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/life-insurance/northwestern-mutual-life-insurance-review/) | 4.9 | Somewhat unlikely to recommend | Good track record of delivering value over time | High costs and aggressive sales tactics |\n| [Penn Mutual](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/life-insurance/penn-mutual-life-insurance-review/) | 5.2 | Somewhat likely to recommend | Competitive rates and a flexible underwriting process | Misleading agents and difficulty withdrawing funds |\n\n* * *\n\n## Cost of Whole Life Insurance\n\nThe most important factor in choosing a whole life insurance policy is to understand that the premium is not the ‘cost’ of a whole life insurance policy. The cost is what’s deducted from that premium for ‘cost of insurance’ charges and policy expenses. To determine the costs on a whole life insurance policy, ask the company or agent for a calculation of all internal policy costs.\n\n[Barry D. Flagg](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/advisory-board/life-insurance/barry-d-flagg/),founder of Veralytic\n\n### Average Monthly Cost for a $250,000 Whole Life Insurance Policy\n\n**The average premium for a whole life insurance policy is$158 a month**for a $250,000 policy for a 30-year-old female and$169 a month for a 30-year-old male, according to Forbes Advisor research based on the lowest quotes we found online for healthy nonsmokers.Here’s a look at monthly cost for females and males ages 30, 40 and 50.\n\n| Age | Average monthly cost for a female buyer | Average monthly cost for a male buyer |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Age 30** | $158 | $169 |\n| **Age 40** | $227 | $225 |\n| **Age 50** | $340 | $382 |\n\n### Average Monthly Cost for a$500,000 Whole Life Insurance Policy\n\n**The average cost of whole life insurance is $313 a month**for a $500,000 policy for a 30-year-old female and $443 a month for a 30-year-old male, according to Forbes Advisor research, based on the lowest quotes we found online for healthy nonsmokers.Here’s a look at monthly cost for females and males ages 30, 40 and 50.\n\n| Age | Average monthly cost for female | Average monthly cost for male |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Age 30** | $313 | $443 |\n| **Age 40** | $449 | $490 |\n| **Age 50** | $676 | $759 |\n\n* * *\n\n## Factors That Affect the Cost of Whole Life Insurance\n\nThe coverage amount you select will have a large impact on your premium. Other factors that typically affect whole life insurance costs include the following.\n\n## Get Instant Life Insurance Quotes from Top Insurers\n\nCompare Policies Hassle-Free, No Login\n\n[Compare Quotes](https://rate.lifequotes.com/liferequest/controller?reqid=qstermindex&REF=60642)\n\n### Age and Gender\n\nThese details help life insurance companies to determine your life expectancy.\n\n### Health\n\nYour health, including height, weight, prescriptions, medical conditions, smoking status, substance abuse history and the health history of your parents and siblings help insurers predict your life expectancy. Your life insurance medical exam results (if required) will also be assessed.\n\n### Driving Record\n\nLife insurers often consider driving record infractions, such as DUIs and reckless driving, when determining your risk level.\n\n### Criminal Record\n\nMajor felonies and multiple felonies will often result in a decline.\n\n### Risky Hobbies and Occupation\n\nRisky hobbies like piloting planes and scuba diving can lead to higher rates or even a decline. Risky jobs can also affect your quotes and whether you’ll be offered a policy.\n\n### Credit and Finances\n\nLife insurers sometimes use risk scores that factor in credit and public records such as bankruptcies.\n\nExpert tip\n\n## How To Choose the Best Whole Life Insurance\n\n![Image 79: Ashlee Valentine](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/80x80/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/Ashlee-Tilford-e1701361587850.jpg)\n\nAshlee Valentine\n\nEditor\n\n![Image 80: Jason Metz](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/80x80/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Jason-Metz-headshot-scaled-e1621974639148.jpg)\n\nJason Metz\n\nEditor\n\n![Image 81: Michelle Megna](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/80x80/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Michelle-Megna.jpeg)\n\nMichelle Megna\n\nEditor\n\n![Image 82: Ashlee Valentine](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/80x80/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/Ashlee-Tilford-e1701361587850.jpg)\n\nAshlee Valentine\n\nEditor\n\n![Image 83: Ashlee Valentine](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/80x80/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/Ashlee-Tilford-e1701361587850.jpg)\n\nAshlee Valentine\n\nEditor\n\n![Image 84: Jason Metz](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/80x80/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Jason-Metz-headshot-scaled-e1621974639148.jpg)\n\nJason Metz\n\nEditor\n\n![Image 85: Michelle Megna](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/80x80/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Michelle-Megna.jpeg)\n\nMichelle Megna\n\nEditor\n\n### Review Dividend History and Dividend Options\n\nIf being paid dividends is one of your life insurance goals, I encourage you to inquire if dividends are paid by the companies you’re considering. If it pays dividends, ask about its dividend history.\n\n### Consider the Company’s Financial Strength\n\nSince a whole life policy is a long-term contract, I recommend that you always consider the company’s financial strength. This will help you feel confident that they will be able to pay future claims. In contrast, a poor rating could help you avoid a bad situation with a company that isn’t financially stable.\n\n### Ask About Life Insurance Riders\n\nSome policies come with built-in riders and others don’t. Most life insurance companies offer riders as add-ons to a whole life policy. If you need to make customizations to your policy, considering riders is a way to achieve that. Just be sure to weigh the cost of the rider against its benefit, because whole life policies are already expensive without add-ons.\n\n* * *\n\n## How Much Whole Life Insurance Do I Need?\n\nBuying enough life insurance coverage is important, of course. There are a lot of things to consider when deciding[how much life insurance you need](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/life-insurance/how-much-life-insurance-do-you-really-need/). Our life insurance calculator can help simplify that decision.\n\n## How much life insurance do you need?\n\nAnswer simple questions in our 3 step process\n\n![Image 86: Life Insurance](https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/fit-in/x/https://www.forbes.com/advisor/wp-content/themes/fadv/assets/img/life-insurance.png)\n\n1\n\n2\n\n3\n\nHow much annual income would your dependents need?\n\nHow long would your dependents need financial support?\n\nNext\n\n2/3\n\nLet's calculate your life insurance need\n\n2\n\n3\n\nHow much debt do you need to pay off?\n\nIf you want to help with the cost of college tuition, how much would you like to cover?\n\nHow much do you want to add for burial expenses?\n\nNext\n\n3/3\n\nLet's calculate your life insurance need\n\n3\n\nHow much savings do you have?\n\nIf you already have life insurance, enter the total coverage amount\n\nGet Results\n\nAmount of life insurance needed\n\n1,406,600\n\nDetails that you have entered\n\nHow much annual income would your dependents need?\n\n30,000\n\nHow much debt do you need to pay off?\n\n160,000\n\nHow long would your dependents need financial support?\n\n16 years\n\nIf you want to help with the cost of college tuition, how much would you like to 