But there are situations that could lead to a tax bill, such as withdrawing cash value from the policy or surrendering it.\n\nSee our guide to [life insurance and taxes](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/life-insurance/is-life-insurance-taxable/).\n\n### What is the difference between whole and term life insurance?\n\nWhen considering [whole life vs. term life insurance](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/life-insurance/term-life-vs-whole-life-insurance/), there are many differences. Term life insurance locks in rates for a level term length and is the most inexpensive form of life insurance. Whole life insurance is often expensive but offers fixed premiums and fixed cash value growth and can last a lifetime.\n\n### Can you borrow money from a whole life policy?\n\nIf you have [cash value](https://www.forbes.com/advisor/life-insurance/cash-value-life-insurance/) in a whole life insurance policy you can take a loan against the money or withdraw it. This money can be used for anything from supplementing retirement savings to paying for a child’s college tuition.\n\nWhen you buy a whole life insurance policy, your policy illustration will show you how fast your cash value may grow over the years, but be sure to ask the agent or insurer to demonstrate the reasonableness of the dividend interest crediting rate used in the calculation of that growth.\n\n### What age is best to buy whole life insurance?\n\nAs with all types of life insurance, the younger you are when you purchase whole life insurance, the lower your premium will be. But in addition to lower premiums, buying a policy when you are younger also means there should be more time for your cash value to accumulate. So, while there is no specific best age to buy whole life insurance, the sooner you can buy it, the better.\n\nInformation provided on Forbes Advisor is for educational purposes only. Your financial situation is unique and the products and services we review may not be right for your circumstances. We do not o